Creating an Analysis dataset

As previosly mentioned,this dataset records variables to assess learning, understanding and attitudes of people towards statistics. The next steps take a look at some of these variables, namely

  • Attitude: Global attitude toward statistics

  • Deep: Deep approach to learning, which involves gaining an in-depth understanding

  • Surf: Surface approach, consisting primarily of memorizing without understanding

  • Stra: Strategic approach, which students apply in the face of constraints such as deadlines and syllabus

1. Scaling vectors to their original values:

Now, to create an analysis dataset, we need to keep in mind that some parameters are aggregates of two or more variables. These are:

  1. Attitude = Da + Db + Dc + Dd + De + Df + Dg + Dh + Di + Dj

  2. Deep = d_sm + d_ri + d_ue, and

  • d_sm = D03 + D11 + D19 + D27

  • d_ri = D07 + D14 + D22 + D30

  • d_ue = D06 + D15 + D23 + D31

  1. Stra = st_os + st_tm, where

  • st_os = ST01 + ST09 + ST17 + ST25

  • st_tm = ST04 + ST12 + ST20 + ST28

  1. Surf = su_lp + su_um + su_sb, where

  • su_lp = SU02 + SU10 + SU18 + SU26

  • su_um = SU05 + SU13 + SU21 + SU29

  • su_sb = SU08 + SU16 + SU24 + SU32

In order to scale Attitude, we need to divide it by the number of variables that constitute it.This is easily done by creating a new variable and assigning the new value to it

Hence,

# divide each number in the column "Attitude" by 10

# create column 'attitude' by scaling the column "Attitude"
learn$attitude <- learn$Attitude / 10

Now for the other variables, since “deep”, “Surf” and “stra” do not exist in this dataset, we must create them by aggregating and averaging their constituents

But first, lemme access the dplyr library

library(dplyr)

# questions related to deep, surface and strategic learning
deep_questions <- c("D03", "D11", "D19", "D27", "D07", "D14", "D22", "D30","D06",  "D15", "D23", "D31")
surface_questions <- c("SU02","SU10","SU18","SU26", "SU05","SU13","SU21","SU29","SU08","SU16","SU24","SU32")
strategic_questions <- c("ST01","ST09","ST17","ST25","ST04","ST12","ST20","ST28")

# select the columns related to deep learning 
deep_columns <- select(learn, one_of(deep_questions))
# and create column 'deep' by averaging
learn$deep <- rowMeans(deep_columns)

# select the columns related to surface learning 
surface_columns <- select(learn, one_of(surface_questions))
# and create column 'surf' by averaging
learn$surf <- rowMeans(surface_columns)

# select the columns related to strategic learning 
strategic_columns <- select(learn, one_of(strategic_questions))
# and create column 'stra' by averaging
learn$stra <- rowMeans(strategic_columns)
# and create column 'stra' by averaging

Part 2: Data Analysis

For this section, we will be using the dataset “learning2014”, that we created in the previous section. It is part of the dataset from the International Survey of Approaches to Learning. The data uses several variables to measure learning strategies and approaches, understanding and attitute of people towards statistics. We have selected the parameters “Gender” (gender), “Age” (Age), Attitude” (attitude), “Deep approach” (deep), “Surface approach”(surf), Strategic approach” (stra), and “Points” (Points) to analyse the data.

Assessing relations between variables

ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20)))

The above graphs give us an idea about the data, for example:

  • The distribution of age varies significantly with gender, with the women being significantly younger than men on average

  • Surface learning is significantly influenced by gender, with women more inclined to adopt the surface approach.

  • Employing the surface approach to learning results in significantly lower points, as is evident by the significant, negative correlation between surf and Points

  • Scoring a higher value on Attitude also resuts in higher points, as is evident by the significant positive correlation between the two

Linear Regression

We attempt to use multiple linear regression to see what combination of variables has a significant effect on the variable “Points”. Therefore,, “Points” is the target variable in these models.

# We create a regression model with the three learning approaches "stra", "surf" and "deep" as explanatory variables

a <- lm(Points~stra+surf+deep, data = learning2014)

# Summarising the model to help us decide weather the explanatory variables have a significant effect on Points.

summary (a)

“Stra” and “Surf” appear to have a significant direct relationship with “Points” at the 0.1 level. This means this significance assumes a 10% error. However, we still have two concerns regarding model “a”:

  1. “deep” does not have a significant relationship with “Points”

  2. The multiple R-squared in 0.04, which means the model can only explain about 4% of the data.

We will try to replace the insignificant variable with another variable and see if it improves the model a bit. We will call this new model “b”.

# Replacing "deep" with "attitude" as an explanatory variable

b <- lm(Points~stra+surf+attitude, data = learning2014)

# Summarising model "b" to help us decide weather the explanatory variables have a significant effect on Points.

summary (b)

Model “d” presents a model where all three explanatory variables have a significant relationship with the target variable.

The next section explains this model

Explaining the model

Model “d” uses the variables “stra”, “Age” and “Attitude” to explain the variations in the target variable , “Points”.

Relationships between variables

  • Both strategic learning and age have a statistically significant, direct relationship with the points obtained by a student in the examination. These explanatory variables are significant at the 0.1 level, meaning this significance also accounts for 1 % of error in the model.

  • The attitude of the students has a significant, direct relationship with the points obtained by a student in the examination. This relationship is significant at the 0.000 level, accounting for 0 % error.

R-squared

The multiple R-squared value of 0.2182 denotes that the model can accurately explain 21.82% of variations in points, using the three explanatory variables.

Validating the Model

The model’s validity will be tested using diagnostic plots using the plot() function.

# Producing diagnostic plots for the model "d"
plot(d)

Residuals v/s Fitted

  • The residuals are distributed randomly and do not have any obvious patterns (although it also appears that more residuals fall above zero). On the whole, the plot indicates that the values deviate more or less randomly from the values predicted by the model.

    • This suggests that the relationship between the variables is more or less linear.

  • There appear to be a few outliers (points 56, 145 and 35).

Normal QQ-plot
  • Not all points coincide with the line, and there appear to be some negative residuals (those falling below the line). This suggests that the data may be skewed and not perfectly normally distributed.
Residuals v/s Leverage
  • The lines indicating Cook’s distance are not visible in our Residuals v/s Leverage Plot. This indicates that all points fall within Cook’s distance. If any points had lied beyond Cook’s distance, they would be the most influential points in our data, removing which could potentially change the interpretation of the model. Therefore, we can assume that model “d” does not have any such points.
